Central venous catheters for haemodialysis: a review.

Akoh JA(1).

Author information:
(1)Plymouth Hospitals NHS Trust, Derriford Hospital, Plymouth PL6 8DH, United 
Kingdom.

Indications for using central venous catheters (CVC) for haemodialysis include 
patients with: exhausted vascular access sites, no suitable vessels, failed 
peritoneal dialysis or short life expectancy. Catheter design and technology 
have changed in recent years to address the perennial problems of poor flow and 
infection. Permanent CVC offer a real alternative to arteriovenous access as 
11-22% of long-term haemodialysis patients use CVC as their permanent vascular 
access. Recent advances in catheter use including measures to avoid insertion 
complications are highlighted. CVC provide mean flow rates of 274-525 ml/min 
with a one year cumulative catheter survival of 47-93%. Tunnelled CVC provide a 
safe and effective long-term access for haemodialysis and are particularly 
suitable for use in developing countries. They are cheaper to maintain and 
remove the temptation to re-use disposable dialysis needles.

